&gt; &gt; Hi:
&gt; &gt;  That is any excellent set of questions. It is useful to remember that
&gt; &gt; while sword knowledge and what should be designated as what goes back at
&gt; &gt; least to the time of the first Ashikaga Shogun, knowledge of tosogu,
&gt; &gt; particularly iron tsuba, goes back no early than the late Bakumatsu era,
&gt; &gt; particularly with the writings of Akiyama and
&gt; &gt; Kawaguchi. The knowledge paradigm is a still expanding one and the
&gt; &gt; boundaries are somewhat indistinct and evolving. There can be a great
&gt; &gt; deal of controversy as to what group something falls into and wildly
&gt; &gt; different opinions as to age of manufacture, that of course hinging on
&gt; &gt; the date of the adoption and substantial spread of the use of
&gt; &gt; uchi-gatana. All one needs to do is to watch the moving time line in the
&gt; &gt; writings of the late Sasano Masayuki.
&gt; &gt;  My advice would be to be conservative in what you submit unless it is a
&gt; &gt; piece about which you have a great deal of curiosity and it being of
&gt; &gt; good workmanship, preservation and aesthetic content. On the other hand
&gt; &gt; one can not sell short the impact that papers have on the value of
&gt; &gt; fittings and the certainty with which they can be sold at a predictable
&gt; &gt; price, if that is of relevance to you.
&gt; &gt;  Arnold
